Issues.Body:
**What version of Tailwind CSS are you using?**
v4.1.7

**Describe your issue**
Hi! Thank you for your big work with tailwind 4.

We have a problem with responsive modifiers for our components using tailwind 4.
Example usage: `<div class="button is-small sm:is-big">example</div>`

With tailwind 3 it's very easy to implement:

```
@layer components {
    .button {
        @apply h-10;
        &.is-small { @apply h-8; }
        &.is-big { @apply h-12; }
    }
}
```

How we can achive this using tailwind 4? `@utility` don't working as expected

We're using Tailwind CSS v4 with Next.js v15 (App Router) in our project.
We style our components using the @apply directive in combination with nested CSS selectors, like so:

### üí° Code Example
```
.btn {
  @apply inline-flex items-center cursor-pointer justify-center gap-x-1.5 rounded-lg font-medium transition-all duration-200 focus:outline-none;

  &-lg {
    @apply h-12 px-4 min-w-[108px] text-d-subtitle1;
  }

  &-contained {
    @apply text-white;

    &-primary {
      @apply bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark hover:shadow-primary;
    }

    &:disabled {
      @apply cursor-not-allowed bg-disabled/20 text-disabled/80;
    }
  }
}

```

‚úÖ Expected Behavior
All nested styles (like .btn-lg, .btn-contained-primary, .btn-contained:disabled, etc.) should be included in the production CSS build.

‚ùå Actual Behavior
In development mode (next dev), everything works perfectly.

In production mode (next build && next start), all nested styles (e.g., &-lg, &-contained, etc.) are missing from the final CSS output.

### üì¶ Project Environment

```
Next.js: 15.x (App Router)
Tailwind CSS: 4.x
PostCSS config: using tailwind nesting
```
### Tailwind-related config:
```
const config = {
  plugins: {
    "@tailwindcss/postcss": {},
    "postcss-nested": {},
  },
};
export default config;
```
### üìå Notes
It seems like Tailwind‚Äôs nesting support works correctly in dev mode but is not preserved in the production build process when using the native &-modifier nesting syntax.

Is this a known limitation or a misconfiguration on our side?
Any help would be appreciated üôè
